% ------------------ ABSTRACT ------------------
\begin{abstract}
\small
As students, it is of vital importance to identify the factors that promote or hinder the achievement of good academic performance in higher education. This study explores some of these factors—including their demographics, study habits, parental involvement, extracurricular activities, and academic performance—through the analysis of data collected from $2392$ high school students. To this end, a multinomial analysis is conducted to assess the influence of these factors on the variable \textit{GradeClass}, which classifies students' grades into distinct categories, and the number of explanatory variables is reduced to simplify the model.

The results indicate that parental support, academic tutoring, and participation in extracurricular activities—particularly sports—have a significant positive impact on students’ performance. In contrast, variables such as gender, ethnicity, and parental education level show no clear effect. Absenteeism is also found to negatively influence academic outcomes, while the effect of study time is only marginal. This analysis provides meaningful insights for educational research, predictive modeling, and statistical analysis, as well as serving as an incentive for the implementation of support measures that promote academic success.

\end{abstract}

\vspace{0.6cm}
\tableofcontents
\end{center}
\end{titlepage}
\newpage

% ------------------ CONTENT ------------------

\section{Introduction}

The objective of our analysis is to identify the factors that most influence whether a student improves their grades compared to the reference category "F" (failed). The motivation lies in seeking measures to help such students improve their academic performance by analyzing the influencing factors that affect their grades. In addition, this study will help us extend our knowledge of regression models studied during the course.

To this end, we have selected a database that contains comprehensive information on high school students and several factors that can affect their academic performance. The target variable classifies students' grades into distinct categories and will be useful to determine the influence of these factors.

This database has several advantages for our purposes:

\begin{enumerate}
\item First, it contains a high number of observations ($2392$), as well as a large number of regressor variables, which makes the resulting analysis potentially more meaningful.
\item By considering a categorical response variable with more than two categories, we can apply a multinomial logistic method, giving us the opportunity to expand on the knowledge acquired during the course and apply familiar concepts related to linear regression models. Moreover, this requires us to extend the bibliography studied in the course, which is also a good exercise to improve our ability to search for useful and reliable information, in addition to contrasting from different sources.
\item The insights obtained from this analysis could be useful for our upcoming years as students.
\end{enumerate}

\section{The dataset}

We have selected a database that contains comprehensive information on $2392$ high school students, detailing their demographics, study habits, parental involvement, extracurricular activities, and academic performance. The target variable, \textit{GradeClass}, classifies students' grades into distinct categories, providing a robust dataset for educational research, predictive modeling, and statistical analysis. It is part of Kaggle's platform, home to a vast trove of open and accessible data. In order to explore this database, refer to \cite{rabie_el_kharoua_2024}. 

This dataset has been downloaded around $50000$ times, so it has surely been used numerous times for statistical analysis. We can find some of these analyses in the following links:
\begin{itemize}
\item \cite{alvin_2024}. This article delves into the analysis of students' performance using the dataset. Alvin Luyza Pramudya provides a comprehensive breakdown of the factors influencing student performance, utilizing various data visualization techniques to illustrate key insights.
\item We can also find several code solutions in the ``code'' section of the dataset: \href{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rabieelkharoua/students-performance-dataset/code}{analysis with code examples}.
\end{itemize}

The regressor variables can be classified into the following groups: Student Information (\textit{Student ID}, Demographic Details, Study Habits), Parental Involvement, Extracurricular Activities, Academic Performance, and the Target Variable: \textit{GradeClass}.

Let us now review each of the variables involved in the dataset:
\begin{itemize}
\item Student Information:

\textit{Student ID:} A unique identifier assigned to each student (1001 to 3392).

\textit{Age:} The age of the students ranges from 15 to 18 years.

\textit{Gender:} Gender of the students, where 0 represents Male and 1 represents Female.

\textit{Ethnicity:} The ethnicity of the students, coded as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0: Caucasian.
\item 1: African American.
\item 2: Asian.
\item 3: Other.
\end{itemize}

\textit{ParentalEducation:} The education level of the parents, coded as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0: None.
\item 1: High School.
\item 2: Some College.
\item 3: Bachelor's.
\item 4: Higher.
\end{itemize}

\textit{StudyTimeWeekly:} Weekly study time in hours, ranging from 0 to 20.

\textit{Absences:} Number of absences during the school year, ranging from 0 to 30.

\textit{Tutoring:} Tutoring status, where 0 indicates No and 1 indicates Yes.

\item Parental Involvement:

\textit{ParentalSupport:} The level of parental support, coded as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0: None.
\item 1: Low.
\item 2: Moderate.
\item 3: High.
\item 4: Very High.
\end{itemize}

\item Extracurricular Activities:

\textit{Extracurricular:} Participation in extracurricular activities, where 0 indicates No and 1 indicates Yes.

\textit{Sports:} Participation in sports, where 0 indicates No and 1 indicates Yes.

\textit{Music:} Participation in music activities, where 0 indicates No and 1 indicates Yes.

\textit{Volunteering:} Participation in volunteering, where 0 indicates No and 1 indicates Yes.

\item Academic Performance:

\textit{GPA:} Grade Point Average on a scale from 0.0 to 4.0, influenced by study habits, parental involvement, and extracurricular activities.

\item Target Variable: 

\textit{GradeClass:} Classification of students' grades based on GPA:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0: `A' ($\text{GPA} \geq 3.5$).
\item 1: `B' ($3.0 \leq \text{GPA} < 3.5$).
\item 2: `C' ($2.5 \leq \text{GPA} < 3.0$).
\item 3: `D' ($2.0 \leq \text{GPA} < 2.5$).
\item 4: `F' ($\text{GPA} < 2.0$)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

Before proceeding with the analysis, we first load the dataset and verify that there are no missing values (\texttt{NA}s). This step is essential to ensure data integrity and avoid issues during model fitting.

<<include=FALSE>>=
dataf<-read.csv('studentperformance.csv')
dataf$GradeClass <- factor(dataf$GradeClass, labels=c('A','B','C','D','F')) 
# Academic performance level
@

<<>>=
sum(is.na(dataf)==TRUE) 
@

The output confirms that there are no missing values in the dataset. Now, we can get a first look at the dataset by summarizing its variables using the known function \texttt{summary()}. 

<<include=FALSE>>=
summary(dataf)
@

We present the obtained results in two separate tables: one for the numerical variables and the other for the categorical ones.

